%I A096002 #20 Jun 15 2026 00:44:50
%S A096002 0,1,2,2,4,2,6,4,4,3,10,3,12,4,3,8,16,4,18,4,4,6,22,5,8,7,10,5,28,2,
%T A096002 30,16,5,9,5,7,36,10,6,6,40,3,42,7,5,12,46,9,12,7,7,8,52,10,6,7,8,15,
%U A096002 58,3,60,16,6,32,6,3,66,10,9,3,70,13,72,19,7,11,7,4,78,10
%N A096002 Let {b(n)} = A095996; then a(n) = number of terms {b(1),b(2),...,b(n-1)} which are coprime to n.
%C A096002 From _Chai Wah Wu_, Jun 13 2026: (Start)
%C A096002 It is clear that the prime factors of A095996(n) are the primes < n that do not divide n.
%C A096002 This implies that a(n) is the number of integers 0<i<n such that all prime factors of n is either a prime factor of i or larger or equal to i.
%C A096002 If n>1 and p_1<p_2<p_3<...<p_r are the distinct prime factors of n, then the number of integers in the range [p_i, p_{i+1}) that satisfy the above condition is floor(p_{i+1}/(p_1*p_2*...*p_i)). By looking at the numbers in the ranges [1,p_i), [p_i, p_{i+1}), ..., [p_{r}, n) that satisfy the above condition, it follows that
%C A096002 a(n) = p_1+floor(p_2/p_1)+floor(p_3/(p_1*p_2))+...+floor(p_r/(p_1*p_2*...*p_{r-1}))+floor(n/(p_1*p_2*...*p_r))-2.
%C A096002 As a consequence, we have the following special cases:
%C A096002 1. if n = p^k for p prime, then a(n) = p^(k-1)+p-2, i.e. if n = p^2 for p prime, then a(n) = 2(p-1).
%C A096002 2. a(primorial(k)) = 2 for k>1, where primorial(k) = A002110(k). Bertrand's postulate implies that floor(prime(i+1)/primorial(i)) = 0 for i>1. Apply this to the formula above.
%C A096002 3. a(10^k) = 10^(k-1)+2 for k>0. (End)
%H A096002 Chai Wah Wu, <a href="/A096002/b096002.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a> (terms 1..1000 from Andrew Howroyd)
%F A096002 If p is prime, then a(p) = p-1.
%t A096002 f[n_] := f[n] = Select[Divisors[n! ], GCD[ #, n] == 1 &][[ -1]]; Table[ Length[ Select[ Range[n - 1], GCD[ f[ # ], n] == 1 &]], {n, 2, 33}]
%o A096002 (PARI) seq(n)={my(v=vector(n, n, denominator(n^n/n!))); vector(n, n, sum(k=1, n-1, gcd(v[k],n)==1));} \\ _Andrew Howroyd_, Nov 05 2019
%o A096002 (Python)
%o A096002 from sympy import isprime, primefactors
%o A096002 def A096002(n):
%o A096002     if isprime(n) or n == 1: return n-1
%o A096002     q, c = 1, -2
%o A096002     for p in sorted(primefactors(n)):
%o A096002         c += p//q
%o A096002         q *= p
%o A096002     return int(c+n//q) # _Chai Wah Wu_, Jun 13 2026
%Y A096002 Cf. A095996.
%K A096002 nonn
%O A096002 1,3
%A A096002 _Robert G. Wilson v_, Jul 19 2004, based on a suggestion from _Leroy Quet_, Jun 18 2004
%E A096002 a(33) - a(41) from _Robert G. Wilson v_, May 05 2013
